transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello! Thank you for having me. I’m glad to be here and share my experiences. Please go ahead with your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! As I mentioned, my name is Aubrey, and I’m 45 years old. I live in rural Kentucky with my husband and our kids. I’ve been a stay-at-home mom for quite a while now, and honestly, it keeps me busy! I have a high school diploma, and while I’ve thought about going back to school, it’s hard to find the time with everything going on at home. We live on a middle-income budget, which can be challenging sometimes, especially when it comes to healthcare access. I have Medicaid, which helps, but I still find it difficult to get to appointments. My lifestyle is pretty sedentary, and I smoke occasionally, which I know isn’t great for my health. Overall, I'm not planning on having more children since I have four already, but I want to make sure I'm taking care of myself and my family. How about you? What else would you like to know?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Of course! I first learned I was pregnant with my oldest child about 20 years ago. I remember feeling a mix of excitement and anxiety, as it was such a big change in my life. Over the years, I had three more pregnancies, all of which were vaginal deliveries. Each time was a bit different, but I generally had the usual symptoms like morning sickness and fatigue. I tried to take care of myself as best as I could, but I didn’t always have the best support or access to healthcare during those times. 

I have to admit, I didn’t have regular prenatal care for all my pregnancies. Sometimes it was hard to get to the clinic, especially with the kids at home, and I didn’t always feel like I could ask for help. My husband worked a lot, so it fell on me to manage everything, including the appointments. I think that might have contributed to some challenges I faced, like the anemia I was diagnosed with after my last pregnancy. 

Would you like to know more about any specific pregnancies or experiences during that time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
I sought prenatal care for my first pregnancy pretty early on, maybe around the eighth week. I remember feeling a bit overwhelmed, trying to figure out what I needed to do. The clinic I went to was about a half-hour away, and getting there with my schedule was tough, especially with my husband working and the other kids at home. 

The experience itself was a bit mixed. The staff were generally nice, but I didn’t feel like I had enough time to ask all the questions I had. I remember feeling nervous during the appointments and wishing I could have someone with me for support. It felt like a lot of information to take in, and I often left feeling unsure if I was doing everything right. 

For my other pregnancies, I didn’t always go as early or as regularly as I should have. Sometimes I’d miss appointments because of child care issues or just feeling too exhausted. Looking back, I can see how that might have affected my health and the health of my babies. I wish I had known more about the importance of regular check-ups and how to advocate for myself when it came to my care. 

Did you want to know more about how my access to care changed with each pregnancy or anything else?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancies, I mostly received care from a local clinic that was part of a larger healthcare network. The providers there were usually nurse practitioners or midwives, and while they were kind, I didn’t always feel a strong connection with any one of them. It was often different faces each time I went in, which made it hard to build a trusting relationship. 

I remember feeling like I was just another patient in the system, and sometimes I felt rushed during my appointments. I would try to ask questions, but it often felt like they were on a tight schedule, so I didn’t always get the thorough answers I needed. I think that made me hesitant to bring up some of my concerns, especially since I was juggling so much at home.

I did appreciate that they offered some educational resources, but I often wished I had someone who could sit down with me and really go over everything in detail. Having someone I could trust and rely on for my care would have made a huge difference. 

Do you want to know about any specific experiences with the healthcare providers or how I felt about the care I received?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Well, during my pregnancies, the frequency of my appointments varied quite a bit. For my first pregnancy, I think I was supposed to go in every four weeks initially, but as my pregnancies progressed, it became more frequent—maybe every two weeks or once a week in the later stages. However, I found it challenging to keep up with that schedule consistently. 

A typical visit usually started with me checking in at the front desk and then waiting in the exam room for a nurse or provider to come in. They would usually ask me a few questions about how I was feeling, check my weight, and take my blood pressure. Then, they would listen to the baby's heartbeat, which was always a relief to hear. 

I remember there being a lot of information shared quickly—like what tests I needed and what to expect in the coming weeks. Sometimes, they would hand me pamphlets or printouts, but honestly, it felt overwhelming to process everything in that short time. I often had questions about things like nutrition, exercise, and any symptoms I was experiencing, but by the time I thought to ask, it felt like the appointment was already wrapping up. 

I wish I had more time to discuss my worries or any specific health concerns I had, especially since I was dealing with things like anemia. It was frustrating to feel like I had to manage everything on my own without a clear understanding of my health needs. 

Would you like to know more about the specific challenges I faced during these visits or anything else related to my appointment experiences?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you experienced any health concerns or complications during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Yes, I have experienced some health concerns during my pregnancies. One of the major issues was anemia, which I was diagnosed with after my last pregnancy. I remember feeling extremely fatigued, and it was tough to keep up with everything at home while also taking care of a newborn. I didn’t realize how serious anemia could be at the time, and I wish I had understood the signs and symptoms better.

Additionally, during some of my pregnancies, I dealt with gestational diabetes for a brief period, which was a bit scary. I had to monitor my diet more closely, and that added another layer of stress to an already busy time. I didn’t have a lot of support or guidance on how to manage it, which made it difficult to navigate.

There were also times when I felt like I wasn’t gaining enough weight or that my weight was a concern—especially since I’ve struggled with obesity. I know that can affect pregnancy, but I didn’t always feel like I had the right information or support to help me manage my health. 

Overall, I think those health concerns impacted my pregnancies and my ability to enjoy that time as much as I could have. I often worried about how my health would affect my babies and if I was doing everything I needed to do for them. 

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my health concerns, or would you like me to share more about how I managed those issues?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What medications or supplements are you currently taking?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Currently, I’m not taking any specific medications, but I do take a daily multivitamin. After my last pregnancy, my doctor recommended that I take iron supplements to help with my anemia, but I haven’t been very consistent with that. I often forget to take them or don’t prioritize it, especially with everything else going on at home.

I also try to eat a balanced diet, but with my busy schedule, I sometimes rely on quick meals that might not be the healthiest. I know there are certain foods that can help with my anemia, like leafy greens and beans, but it can be hard to make those a regular part of my diet. 

I haven’t been prescribed anything for my prediabetes, but I’m aware that I need to be careful about my sugar intake and try to incorporate some healthier choices into my meals. 

Do you want to know more about my dietary habits or anything else related to the medications and supplements I take?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your diet and nutrition during pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancies, my diet and nutrition were a bit of a mixed bag. I tried to eat healthily, but with so much going on—taking care of the kids, managing the household—it was often challenging to prioritize my own nutrition. 

In the early stages of my pregnancies, I had a lot of cravings, which sometimes led me to indulge in things I probably shouldn't have. I remember craving things like ice cream and snacks that weren't the healthiest. I did try to eat fruits and veggies, but honestly, I often ended up relying on quick meals or convenience foods because cooking while managing everything else was tough. 

I was aware that I needed to focus on getting enough nutrients, especially with my anemia. I tried to incorporate foods rich in iron, like red meat and beans, but some days it just didn’t happen. I also know that I should’ve paid more attention to my carbohydrate intake, especially when I had gestational diabetes. But I felt overwhelmed trying to balance everything, and I didn’t have a lot of guidance on how to manage my diet effectively during that time.

Looking back, I really wish I had more support or resources to help me understand what I should be eating and how to make better choices. It’s something I still struggle with now, trying to maintain a healthy diet while managing my busy life.

Would you like to know more about my specific dietary habits during my pregnancies, or how I’ve tried to improve my nutrition since then?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How have you been feeling emotionally during your pregnancy?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Emotionally, my pregnancies were quite a rollercoaster. There were definitely moments of joy and excitement, especially when I felt the baby moving or heard the heartbeat for the first time. Those were really special moments that I cherished. However, I also experienced a lot of anxiety and stress throughout my pregnancies.

With each pregnancy, I found myself worrying about my health and the health of my babies. Given my struggles with anemia and gestational diabetes, I was always concerned about whether I was doing enough to ensure a healthy pregnancy. Sometimes, I felt overwhelmed by the responsibility of caring for my other children while also preparing for a new baby. I often put a lot of pressure on myself to be a good mom and to manage everything perfectly, which only added to my stress.

I also faced feelings of isolation at times. Living in a rural area made it harder to connect with other moms or find support groups. I often felt like I was going through it alone, especially when I had questions or concerns that I didn’t feel comfortable bringing up during my appointments. I wished I had someone to talk to who understood what I was going through.

Looking back, I think that emotional support is just as important as physical health during pregnancy. It’s something I wish I had focused on more. 

Would you like to explore any specific feelings or experiences I had during particular pregnancies, or is there something else related to my emotional health that you’re curious about?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who supports you during your pregnancy? Can you tell me about your support network?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancies, my primary support came from my husband, but it was a bit of a mixed experience. He worked a lot, which meant he was often away during the day, so I had to handle a lot of things on my own. He was always there for me when he could be, and I appreciated his presence during the important moments, like when I had ultrasounds or went into labor. However, because of his work schedule, he sometimes couldn’t attend all the appointments or be as involved as I would have liked.

I also had my children to think about, and while they were excited about the new baby, they were still young and needed a lot of my attention. This often made it hard for me to find time for myself or to seek out additional support.

In terms of extended family and friends, I didn’t have a strong support network nearby. Most of my family lives quite a distance away, and while I did have a few friends, they were also busy with their own lives and families. I sometimes felt isolated, especially when I needed someone to talk to about my worries or experiences. 

I really wished I had access to a support group or a community of other moms who could relate to what I was going through. I think having that kind of network would have made a significant difference in how I felt emotionally during my pregnancies. 

Do you want to know more about how I tried to seek support or any specific instances where I felt particularly supported or unsupported?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about your birth plan? What are your preferences for delivery?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Yes, I did think about my birth plans for each of my pregnancies, although I have to admit that they were often more flexible than I initially intended. My preference was always for a vaginal delivery since that was how I had delivered my other children. I felt more comfortable with that process, and I appreciated the idea of a more natural delivery.

I also wanted to have as little intervention as possible, but I found that things don’t always go as planned. For instance, during my last pregnancy, I had some concerns about my anemia and how it might affect my ability to handle labor. So, while I wanted to stick to my preferences, I was also aware that I might need to be open to different options if complications arose.

I usually discussed my preferences with the healthcare providers, but I sometimes felt like those conversations were brief and didn’t cover everything I wanted to address. I wished I had more time to express my thoughts and concerns, especially since I was nervous about the delivery process each time. 

I also thought about having someone with me for support during labor, but I often felt like it would just be my husband. I think I would have benefited from having a doula or a close friend there to help advocate for me and keep me calm. 

Overall, while I had preferences, I learned to be adaptable, knowing that the most important thing was a safe delivery for my baby and me. 

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my birth plans, or perhaps how my experiences influenced my preferences over time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: What sources of information have you used to learn about pregnancy and childbirth?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: During my pregnancies, I relied on a few different sources for information about pregnancy and childbirth. One of the main sources was my healthcare providers during my appointments. They would give me pamphlets and some verbal information, but like I mentioned before, I often felt rushed and didn’t get to discuss everything I wanted to know.

I also turned to the internet for information. I would search for articles and forums about pregnancy, childbirth, and parenting. There were times I found helpful tips or reassuring stories from other moms, but I also encountered a lot of conflicting information, which made it tough to know what to believe. It was overwhelming at times, especially when I was trying to figure out what was best for my health and my babies.

Books were another resource I used. I picked up a few pregnancy books that provided insights into each trimester and what to expect during childbirth. They helped me feel more informed, but I still felt like I needed more personalized guidance.

Despite these sources, I often wished I had a trusted mentor or someone with experience who could guide me through the process. I think having a more direct support system would have made a significant difference in how I felt about my pregnancies and the decisions I needed to make.

Would you like to know more about specific sources I found helpful or how I navigated the information overload during my pregnancies?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How are you managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Managing the financial aspects of pregnancy and preparing for a baby has always been a bit of a juggling act for us. Since we live on a middle-income budget and I have Medicaid coverage, I’ve relied on that for most of my prenatal care. It helps with the costs of doctor visits and any necessary tests, but there are still other expenses that add up quickly.

For instance, while my prenatal care is covered, I’ve had to think about other costs, like maternity clothes and baby supplies. I try to budget for those things, but it can be challenging to set aside money when we have other bills to pay. I usually look for sales or second-hand items to save money, especially since we’ve been through this before and know what we really need for the baby.

I also worry about the costs of delivery, although I know Medicaid covers a lot of it. There’s always that uncertainty about what might happen during labor and if there will be any additional costs if complications arise. It adds a layer of stress, knowing that unexpected expenses can come up.

We’ve also had discussions about how to prepare for the baby’s arrival, like whether we need to set up a separate room or just make space in our existing setup. With four kids already, we have a lot of supplies, but I still find myself second-guessing what we might need or if we should buy anything new.

Overall, I’ve learned to be resourceful and to prioritize what’s most important. I often find myself balancing our financial situation with the desire to provide everything we can for our newest family member, and it can be a bit overwhelming.

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about how I manage these financial aspects, or perhaps how I’ve prepared for previous pregnancies in terms of budgeting?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How has your pregnancy affected your work or employment situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Well, since I’ve been a stay-at-home mom for quite some time, my pregnancies haven’t directly affected a work or employment situation like they might for someone with a job outside the home. My primary focus has always been on taking care of my children and managing the household. 

However, I do feel that being pregnant added another layer of responsibility and workload on top of my daily tasks. With each pregnancy, I had to balance caring for my other kids while also preparing for the new baby. It sometimes felt overwhelming, especially when I dealt with health concerns like anemia or gestational diabetes. 

Even though I don’t have a job outside the home, I often think about how my health and well-being during pregnancy impact my ability to manage everything. There were times when I felt too tired or unwell to keep up with my usual routines, and that made me worry about how I was handling things for my family. 

I’ve also considered how my role as a stay-at-home mom could change once the baby arrives. It’s a lot of work, and I sometimes wonder if I should look for part-time work or find ways to contribute financially while still being present for my children. 

Overall, while I don’t have a traditional employment situation to navigate, my pregnancies have certainly influenced my daily life and how I manage my responsibilities at home. 

Would you like to know more about my thoughts on work and pregnancy or how I’ve balanced my roles as a mom during this time?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Have you thought about the postpartum period? What plans do you have for after the baby arrives?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Yes, I have thought about the postpartum period, and I have mixed feelings about it. On one hand, I'm excited to welcome a new baby and start that new chapter, but on the other hand, I know that the postpartum period can be quite challenging. With my previous pregnancies, I struggled with feelings of exhaustion and sometimes even a bit of postpartum depression. I want to be prepared this time around to take care of myself as well as the baby.

I’ve been trying to think about how to manage my time and responsibilities after the baby arrives. I know that being a mom to four kids will be a lot of work, and I worry about how I’ll handle everything, especially if I feel overwhelmed or fatigued again. I want to make sure I have a support system in place, so I’ve talked to my husband about how we can share responsibilities and make sure I have some time to rest when I need it.

I’ve also considered reaching out to friends or family for help, even if it’s just someone to talk to or offer advice. I wish I had more support from my community, whether that's other moms or local groups. I think it would help to have people around who understand what I’m going through and can offer encouragement.

As for plans, I want to focus on self-care and making time for my mental health. I know that taking care of myself is important, not just for me, but for my family as well. I’ve also been thinking about how to incorporate healthy habits into my daily routine, especially with my prediabetes and anemia. I want to ensure I’m eating well and finding ways to be active, even with a newborn.

Overall, I’m trying to be more mindful of the postpartum period this time and make plans to support my well-being. 

Is there anything specific you’d like to know about my plans for after the baby arrives or how I’m preparing for the postpartum period?

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Thank you for your time and for sharing your experiences with me. This concludes our interview.
